Summary:  
We conducted research into the various features and methods that are already available in OpenCV to figure out which of these features might be useful for us to process the live footage and reduce noise. 

## Detect Multiscale

cascade.detectMultiScale(img) \-\> detect the face region used to cut the image.

## 

## Greyscale Conversion

cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR\_BGR2GRAY) \-\> reduces input complexity without losing the information.

Data Augmentation  
cv2.flip(src, flipCode), cv2.getRotationMatrix2D(center, angle, scale), cv2.warpAffine(img, M, size) \-\> increase robustness. Perhaps inverting the image can also provide more information for the classifier, some kind of symmetry. 

## Linear Filtering

[cv.morphologyEx](https://docs.opencv.org/4.12.0/d4/d86/group__imgproc__filter.html#ga67493776e3ad1a3df63883829375201f)(src, op, kernel) \-\> clearing noise, if converting the image into grayscale, clearing the noise point for a better recognition for the features.

## [Image Thresholding](https://docs.opencv.org/4.x/d7/d4d/tutorial_py_thresholding.html)

If the pixel value is smaller than or equal to the threshold, it is set to 0, otherwise it is set to a maximum value. The function cv.threshold is used to apply the thresholding. Basically helps to reduce noise by making the dark grey areas darker and the light grey areas lighter. 

img \= [cv.imread](https://docs.opencv.org/4.x/d4/da8/group__imgcodecs.html#gaffb68fce322c6e52841d7d9357b9ad2d)('sudoku.png', cv.IMREAD\_GRAYSCALE)  
assert img is not None, "file could not be read, check with os.path.exists()"  
img \= [cv.medianBlur](https://docs.opencv.org/4.x/d4/d86/group__imgproc__filter.html#ga564869aa33e58769b4469101aac458f9)(img,5)  
ret,th1 \= [cv.threshold](https://docs.opencv.org/4.x/d7/d1b/group__imgproc__misc.html#gae8a4a146d1ca78c626a53577199e9c57)(img,127,255,cv.THRESH\_BINARY)  
th2 \= [cv.adaptiveThreshold](https://docs.opencv.org/4.x/d7/d1b/group__imgproc__misc.html#ga72b913f352e4a1b1b397736707afcde3)(img,255,cv.ADAPTIVE\_THRESH\_MEAN\_C,\\  
           cv.THRESH\_BINARY,11,2)  
th3 \= [cv.adaptiveThreshold](https://docs.opencv.org/4.x/d7/d1b/group__imgproc__misc.html#ga72b913f352e4a1b1b397736707afcde3)(img,255,cv.ADAPTIVE\_THRESH\_GAUSSIAN\_C,\\  
           cv.THRESH\_BINARY,11,2)  
titles \= \['Original Image', 'Global Thresholding (v \= 127)',  
           'Adaptive Mean Thresholding', 'Adaptive Gaussian Thresholding'\]  
images \= \[img, th1, th2, th3\]  
Specific details are too mathematically heavy, but the idea is that we are able to remove noise in the pictures, so that we can make the contrast higher.

## [Image Gradients](https://docs.opencv.org/4.x/d5/d0f/tutorial_py_gradients.html)

![][image2] 

* cv2.Laplacian() \-\>detects edges in all directions at once and enhances rapid brightness transitions.  
* cv.CV\_64F / cv.CV\_16S (output depth): higher-precision data types used when computing gradients.  
  * Contribution: preserves negative gradients so both dark→light and light→dark edges are detected.

## Edge Detection

cv2.Canny \-\> Edge detection in images. Takes in min val and max val. One way to start building a facial recognition model.

cv.watershed \-\> Separate background from foreground and sharpen boundaries. Helps work around noise for facial recognition models.

## Background Removal

cv.grabCut \-\> Foreground extraction/background removal. May require frequent manual adjustments. Could help with isolating faces and making the frames easier to work with.

## Image Matching

[**cv.matchTemplate()**](https://docs.opencv.org/4.12.0/df/dfb/group__imgproc__object.html#ga586ebfb0a7fb604b35a23d85391329be) \-\> finding image in a bigger image(more of what ml should do), if the image are all from the same angle, it should directly detect the image in the video stream, may be useful for testing.

Denoising  
[**cv.fastNlMeansDenoising()**](https://docs.opencv.org/4.12.0/d1/d79/group__photo__denoise.html#ga4c6b0031f56ea3f98f768881279ffe93) \-\> just a integrated version of denoising I guess, may fits all kinds of denoising, this is a grayscale version, there is a colored version.
